m/uploads/default/original/2X/f/f76d17976d6b2c69167c10a1a18ad57e365c59be.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/4/40b20273217e1b18c59bbcd3f48b6ecca758706c.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/e/ed778e8997d71cec69276a0a32dbb603eb48ffc9.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/4/45a3d4a0cf7fba317fc285700037318d60dfa27d.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/0/0f1453d113f15d43bcedff19610229a7f75ebf60.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/6/6708d8959440b8805afc8470858dfedc048bcaa7.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/5/5a0098f13086eababf4f3999ed7201d14098ef6a.jpeg"]},"payload":{"url":"","schema":"20231218A","file":"content.txt","text":"# How to use Git\n\nURL: https://community.origam.com/t/how-to-use-git/3910\n\n@vikter (2025-01-16 14:20:34Z):\n   \nIn this article, we will cover the basics of using Git for individual code versioning.\n One of the key uses of Git is enabling multiple people to collaborate on a single application, but this is outside the scope of this article. Likewise, we will not cover he topic of using remote repositories such as GitHub, GitLab, or BitBucket. \nThe only thing we will show here in this regard is the basic creation of a remote repository in GitHub and sending a copy of the local repository there. \n \n If you\u2019re completely new to Git, you may find  this  and  this  video helpful. \n \n   How to install Git \n In this article, we will demonstrate two different ways to use Git: via the command line (Git Bash) and through an application with a graphical user interface (TortoiseGit). \n Here\u2019s some basic information about both tools, along with links to download them if you don\u2019t already have them installed. \n \n \nGit with command line only \n Here are the download links and general instructions on  how to install Git on any operating system . \n For this guide, we will use Git for Windows, which you can download  here . \n  \n\n\n[Image: https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/e/e823f99e9eca100cdede3676d8ae67ea0590fe18.png]\nDescription: The image features an application icon for \u0022Git Bash.\u0022 The icon consists of a colorful design made up of four overlapping geometric shapes, each in different colors: red, blue, yellow, and green. Below the icon, the text \u0022Git Bash\u0022 is prominently displayed in a bold font, with \u0022App\u0022 listed underneath in a smaller size. The overall appearance suggests a modern and user-friendly interface, likely aimed at developers or users familiar with version control systems.\n\n\n  \n  \n\n\n[Image: https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/6/6b3d9ff3f8ded8027d86f8360b711212959573ec.png]\nDescription: The image displays a command line interface, specifically the MINGW64 terminal, which is likely part of a Git Bash installation. The window title indicates the path \u0022C:/Users/victo\u0022 and the command prompt shows the user\u0027s name as \u0022victo\u0022, followed by the host name \u0022HP-book-Viktor\u0022. The prompt includes the text \u0022MINGW64 ~\u0022 and ends with a dollar sign ($), indicating the terminal is ready for input. The background is black, and there is minimal visible text, suggesting the terminal is in an idle state awaiting commands.\n\n\n  \n \n \n \nTortoiseGit application \n TortoiseGit is a Windows Shell Interface for Git and is based on TortoiseSVN. It\u2019s open source and can be fully built with freely available software. You can download it  here . \n  \n\n\n[Image: https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/6/67e43b0942b467de351773abb57c815ee431298a.png]\nDescription: Text displayed includes \u0022TortoiseGit\u0022 prominently, with a description stating \u0022Git revision control client, implemented as a Windows shell extension and based on TortoiseSVN.\u0022 A website link, \u0022tortoisegit.org,\u0022 is presented in blue text. Accompanying the text is a cartoon turtle with a shell marked \u0022Git.\u0022 The purpose of this image is to provide branding and introductory information about the TortoiseGit software.\n\n\n  \n \n Now that we have Git installed, let\u2019s explore how to use it. \n   Git repository creation \n When creating a new project, a local Git repository is automatically created for you, provided that you leave the relevant option checked. \n  \n\n\n[Image: https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/7/7c114b7575ae114517b2acb1d9feea7921cb865d.png]\nDescription: The image depicts a user interface for creating a new project in a software application. It includes a section labeled \u0022Model Location\u0022 and features a checkbox for \u0022Create GIT repository,\u0022 which is checked. The UI is designed to facilitate project setup, indicating that the user can specify a model location and optionally initialize a GIT repository for version control. In addition, there is a back navigation arrow labeled \u0022New Project\u0022 at the top left.\n\n\n  \n In this case, an invisible  .git  directory is created in your project folder. This is where all Git\u2019s internal data is stored. \n  \n\n\n[Image: https://community.origam.","vector_provider":"AI.Ollama.OllamaTextEmbeddingGenerator","vector_generator":"__","last_update":"2026-05-01T23:39:11"},"vector":[-0.031514183,0.01828145,-0.035180315,0.049008906,0.012490927,-0.032891113,-0.0021687069,-0.0116502205,0.007741117,0.02960059,0.008096039,-0.008592852,-0.027903551,0.013939672,-0.0031040346,-0.014145622,-0.02542905,0.044895954,0.026046593,-0.02107571,0.013842908,-0.009124586,0.049500536,0.02515659,0.0041074636,-0.0027633864,0.014302341,0.007716263,0.020528294,-0.0022484777,0.014401993,-0.011249812,0.017709749,-0.03714362,-0.045948233,-0.00017785489,-0.0060763247,0.017806187,-0.01074316,-0.0043868916,0.02707111,0.002645779,0.003204857,-0.017910657,-0.0066780075,-0.044389933,-0.005421491,-0.